 TONGUE"]

00:24:30.540 --> 00:24:33.420
ANANT SHUKLA: So obviously
some very strong war motifs,

00:24:33.420 --> 00:24:35.429
the video itself as well.

00:24:35.429 --> 00:24:37.720
Tell me a little bit about
the process behind this song

00:24:37.720 --> 00:24:40.280
and if it was any different
from what you just mentioned.

00:24:40.280 --> 00:24:43.350
POLLY SAMSON: Well
this was in a way

00:24:43.350 --> 00:24:44.920
quite a daunting song to write.

00:24:44.920 --> 00:24:46.720
And it was the last
one that I wrote

00:24:46.720 --> 00:24:48.230
for the "Rattle That Lock".

00:24:48.230 --> 00:24:53.430
And it was a piece of music
that was so suggestive of what

00:24:53.430 --> 00:24:55.090
it had to be about.

00:24:55.090 --> 00:25:03.030
And I for some reason felt
inhibited by the enormity

00:25:03.030 --> 00:25:05.820
of that subject, you
know, the wastage of war.

00:25:05.820 --> 00:25:11.350
And so I spent a long time
reading poetry, basically

00:25:11.350 --> 00:25:13.910
the poetry of
conscience, so you know

00:25:13.910 --> 00:25:18.180
poetry written by people who
had served in Afghanistan,

00:25:18.180 --> 00:25:20.040
a lot of different poetry.

00:25:20.040 --> 00:25:21.970
I mean I even read the
poetry of the Taliban.

00:25:21.970 --> 00:25:27.050
I wanted to sort of read a
lot of poetry to do with war.

00:25:27.050 --> 00:25:29.690
And I kind of got really
bogged down in it, I mean.

00:25:29.690 --> 00:25:34.620
And it got to the point where
I couldn't write a word.

00:25:34.620 --> 00:25:37.510
And so I read more and more of
these collections of poetry.

00:25:37.510 --> 00:25:39.971
And in the end David
said, it doesn't matter,

00:25:39.971 --> 00:25:40.720
it doesn't matter.

00:25:40.720 --> 00:25:42.280
You know, if it doesn't
make it on to the album,

00:25:42.280 --> 00:25:43.029
it doesn't matter.

00:25:43.029 --> 00:25:45.750
You know he's very,
very good like that.

00:25:45.750 --> 00:25:48.310
And I think it was
kind of the last day.

00:25:48.310 --> 00:25:50.289
And I thought, oh it's
such a great tune.

00:25:50.289 --> 00:25:52.330
I don't want to be
responsible for this not going

00:25:52.330 --> 00:25:53.400
on the album.

00:25:53.400 --> 00:25:55.310
And I sat in the
sunshine and just

00:25:55.310 --> 00:25:57.630
thought, why am I making
such a meal of this.

00:25:57.630 --> 00:25:58.900
I know what I think.

00:25:58.900 --> 00:26:00.580
I know exactly what I think.

00:26:00.580 --> 00:26:03.880
And I think I wrote the lyric
in maybe 10 minutes once I'd

00:26:03.880 --> 00:26:05.540
give myself a firm talking to.

00:26:05.540 --> 00:26:06.736
ANANT SHUKLA: Yeah.

00:26:06.736 --> 00:26:09.530
I think we want to open
it up to any audience

00:26:09.530 --> 00:26:13.390
Q&amp;A. If you guys
have any questions,

00:26:13.390 --> 00:26:16.299
now's a great time to
ask Polly on everything

00:26:16.299 --> 00:26:17.090
she's talked about.

00:26:19.940 --> 00:26:21.852
We have some mics that
will be coming around.

00:26:29.510 --> 00:26:31.990
AUDIENCE: Polly, when
you write a short story

00:26:31.990 --> 00:26:36.320
you said you have-- you sort
of have it floating your head.

00:26:36.320 --> 00:26:42.620
When you're doing a novel,
are you carrying the ending

00:26:42.620 --> 00:26:45.680
in your head and then you're
just letting the story progress

00:26:45.680 --> 00:26:47.300
and the characters develop?

00:26:47.300 --> 00:26:51.260
You don't really know how you're
going to get to the ending?

00:26:51.260 --> 00:26:53.037
POLLY SAMSON: Yeah.

00:26:53.037 --> 00:26:55.120
It's a great question
because it is very different

00:26:55.120 --> 00:26:57.230
from a short story,
writing a novel.

00:26:57.230 --> 00:27:00.140
And I think it's very
different for different sorts

00:27:00.140 --> 00:27:00.890
of novelists.

00:27:00.890 --> 00:27:03.800
I have a friend who
plots the whole thing.

00:27:03.800 --> 00:27:05.680
And I'm quite envious, really.

00:27:05.680 --> 00:27:08.170
You go look in her
writing room and there it

00:27:08.170 --> 00:27:09.860
is, chapter 1, chapter 2.

00:27:09.860 --> 00:27:11.910
And she knows
everything she's doing

00:27:11.910 --> 00:27:13.540
and it's this
wonderful scaffolding

00:27:13.540 --> 00:27:16.060
and she just hangs the
writing on the scaffolding.

00:27:16.060 --> 00:27:18.970
But I have to admit
that that would bore me.

00:27:18.970 --> 00:27:20.830
I know who my characters are.

00:27:20.830 --> 00:27:23.750
I know what their
moral problems are.

00:27:23.750 --> 00:27:26.224
I know the moral choices
they have to make.

00:27:26.224 --> 00:27:28.390
But other than that, I don't
really know the ending.

00:27:28.390 --> 00:27:29.610
And things change.

00:27:29.610 --> 00:27:33.410
I mean this method writing,
that's when things change.

00:27:33.410 --> 00:27:37.050
I mean walking as that person
and thinking as that person

00:27:37.050 --> 00:27:41.220
and responding to things
as that person makes

00:27:41.220 --> 00:27:44.962
the story and the journey
to the end very different

00:27:44.962 --> 00:27:46.420
from something I
might have thought

00:27:46.420 --> 00:27:48.020
I was doing in the beginning.

00:27:48.020 --> 00:27:49.790
And that's what makes
it exciting actually

00:27:49.790 --> 00:27:54.550
for me is I like the surprises.

00:27:54.550 --> 00:27:57.090
I like the way that
things I thought

00:27:57.090 --> 00:27:59.030
I was going to do just change.

00:27:59.030 --> 00:28:02.060
It's endlessly surprising

00:28:02.060 --> 00:28:04.410
ANANT SHUKLA: Yeah.

00:28:04.410 --> 00:28:06.420
Question in the back.

00:28:06.420 --> 00:28:08.120
AUDIENCE: So
songwriting is something

00:28:08.120 --> 00:28:10.210
that's always interested me.

00:28:10.210 --> 00:28:13.580
And one of the things
that I've always wondered

00:28:13.580 --> 00:28:18.120
is after a certain point,
you become famous, right,

00:28:18.120 --> 00:28:22.885
and you're living a different
sort of life than other people

00:28:22.885 --> 00:28:24.260
and you're seeing
things that are

00:28:24.260 --> 00:28:28.120
different than other people,
than an average person.

00:28:28.120 --> 00:28:34.380
And yet often when artists
become famous their albums,

00:28:34.380 --> 00:28:37.010
not always, will become better
and better and better, OK,

00:28:37.010 --> 00:28:39.093
sometimes worse, but better
and better and better.

00:28:39.093 --> 00:28:41.450
And I have always wondered
how do you actually

00:28:41.450 --> 00:28:45.610
continue to kind of be
hungry, continue to see things

00:28:45.610 --> 00:28:48.525
from the view of
non-famous people

00:28:48.525 --> 00:28:50.900
who have a very different,
potentially, view of the world

00:28:50.900 --> 00:28:52.275
that maybe you
don't have anymore

00:28:52.275 --> 00:28:55.410
and still connect with people.

00:28:55.410 --> 00:28:57.430
It's something I've
just always wondered.

00:28:57.430 --> 00:29:00.280
How does Pink Floyd
or David or you

00:29:00.280 --> 00:29:04.300
get down and still write a song
today that can connect with us?

00:29:04.300 --> 00:29:05.060
Thank you.

00:29:05.060 --> 00:29:06.350
POLLY SAMSON: Thank you.

00:29:06.350 --> 00:29:09.700
I don't feel like I
have a wall anywhere

00:29:09.700 --> 00:29:11.430
built between me and anyone.

00:29:11.430 --> 00:29:14.300
I don't feel famous,
I mean, and I'm not.

00:29:14.300 --> 00:29:18.370
So I can't answer how
it is to be famous.

00:29:18.370 --> 00:29:23.440
But I do know that we
live a very ordinary life.

00:29:23.440 --> 00:29:25.750
We don't-- we live
an ordinary life.

00:29:25.750 --> 00:29:28.090
Our children go to school.

00:29:28.090 --> 00:29:28.880
We cook.

00:29:28.880 --> 00:29:30.210
We walk.

00:29:30.210 --> 00:29:31.460
We walk our dog.

00:29:31.460 --> 00:29:33.130
Our friends are
not famous people.

00:29:33.130 --> 00:29:35.790
Our friends are, you know--
I feel very connected.

00:29:35.790 --> 00:29:40.060
I don't feel my life has changed
because my husband is famous.

00:29:40.060 --> 00:29:43.200
If that answers the question.

00:29:43.200 --> 00:29:46.810
AUDIENCE: Sort of, I mean in the
sense that it's not just fame,

00:29:46.810 --> 00:29:52.300
but it's you first are writing,
when your first writing

00:29:52.300 --> 00:29:56.090
songs, your financial
position or view of the world

00:29:56.090 --> 00:29:58.510
and everything has got to
be very different than once

00:29:58.510 --> 00:30:01.005
you have, whether it's
specifically you that's famous

00:30:01.005 --> 00:30:02.505
or that world that
your living in is

00:30:02.505 --> 00:30:03.939
a very, very different world.

00:30:03.939 --> 00:30:05.980
And I mean, I don't know,
like "Comfortably Numb"

00:30:05.980 --> 00:30:09.194
was written about being
on tour or something

00:30:09.194 --> 00:30:10.610
like that and
something like this.

00:30:10.610 --> 00:30:14.370
That's something that most of
us don't-- it's a great song--

00:30:14.370 --> 00:30:15.970
but something most
of us don't have.

00:30:15.970 --> 00:30:18.840
I guess it's kind of how
do you think you can still

00:30:18.840 --> 00:30:20.030
connect to people.

00:30:20.030 --> 00:30:22.280
POLLY SAMSON: OK there is
a one word answer to that.

00:30:22.280 --> 00:30:23.820
And it's the most
important thing

00:30:23.820 --> 00:30:26.370
that a writer needs to
possess and it's empathy.

00:30:26.370 --> 00:30:27.940
So you know it's
what I talked about.

00:30:27.940 --> 00:30:29.898
It's about, it's like
method writing, you know.

00:30:29.898 --> 00:30:32.920
It is about being able to
get under anyone's skin.

00:30:32.920 --> 00:30:35.860
And you know I
don't think there's

00:30:35.860 --> 00:30:39.000
a writer alive who
hasn't got empathy

00:30:39.000 --> 00:30:40.360
as their greatest skill.

00:30:40.360 --> 00:30:42.568
I mean and if they haven't
they shouldn't be writing.

00:30:46.000 --> 00:30:47.709
ANANT SHUKLA: Another
question here.

00:30:47.709 --> 00:30:49.000
AUDIENCE: So I'll preface this.

00:30:49.000 --> 00:30:51.700
I'm not a published
author but I really

00:30:51.700 --> 00:30:54.719
understand your method writing
that you were discussing,

00:30:54.719 --> 00:30:56.510
that that's kind of
exactly how I do stuff.

00:30:56.510 --> 00:30:59.800
But when I do that, I find that
for every one finished product

00:30:59.800 --> 00:31:02.570
that's like good and goes
somewhere, that's clever

00:31:02.570 --> 00:31:04.362
and other people
might want to read it,

00:31:04.362 --> 00:31:06.820
there's probably at least five
to nine other things I like,

00:31:06.820 --> 00:31:07.944
eh, it kind of petered out.

00:31:07.944 --> 00:31:08.870
It didn't work.

00:31:08.870 --> 00:31:10.830
So you have two
published novels and I

00:31:10.830 --> 00:31:12.560
was wondering how
many did you start

00:31:12.560 --> 00:31:14.900
writing that just didn't
go anywhere or are you able

00:31:14.900 --> 00:31:17.010
to salvage them somehow?

00:31:17.010 --> 00:31:19.369
ANANT SHUKLA: You've got to
silence your inner critic

00:31:19.369 --> 00:31:21.910
because you know you say there
are eight or nine that are not

00:31:21.910 --> 00:31:22.409
working.

00:31:22.409 --> 00:31:24.730
But that's your inner
critic is telling you that.

00:31:24.730 --> 00:31:28.600
And maybe your inner critic
is being too harsh with you.

00:31:28.600 --> 00:31:30.680
Just a thought.

00:31:30.680 --> 00:31:33.470
I don't have a load of
stuff that I've started.

00:31:33.470 --> 00:31:37.320
I tend to kind of-- if I
start something, I finish it.

00:31:37.320 --> 00:31:39.920
But I take a long time
to start something.

00:31:39.920 --> 00:31:42.740
I have to know that
it's going to take time,

00:31:42.740 --> 00:31:46.430
it's going to take energy, and
it's going to be obsessional.

00:31:46.430 --> 00:31:49.810
So I have to know that I'm
jumping into the right pool

00:31:49.810 --> 00:31:52.020
before I take the leap.

00:31:52.020 --> 00:31:55.980
I've written one novel that
didn't reach full gestational

00:31:55.980 --> 00:31:58.890
and it got to
about 20,000 words.

00:31:58.890 --> 00:32:00.960
And my inner critic
was deafening.

00:32:00.960 --> 00:32:04.520
And actually I found it on
an old drive the other day.

00:32:04.520 --> 00:32:06.920
And my inner critic on
that occasion was correct.

00:32:06.920 --> 00:32:08.280
It was terrible.

00:32:08.280 --> 00:32:13.340
But you know I think it's
about starting the right thing

00:32:13.340 --> 00:32:14.695
if that's any help.

00:32:14.695 --> 00:32:16.070
ANANT SHUKLA: That
kind of segues

00:32:16.070 --> 00:32:18.236
to my next question in terms
of what's next for you?

00:32:18.236 --> 00:32:19.000
Another novel?

00:32:19.000 --> 00:32:22.598
Another short story collection?

00:32:22.598 --> 00:32:26.310
POLLY SAMSON: What's next
for me is another novel.

00:32:26.310 --> 00:32:28.940
I've got three novels
kind of float--

00:32:28.940 --> 00:32:31.060
this is the thing about
selecting the right thing.

00:32:31.060 --> 00:32:33.406
There are three ideas kind
of flying around out there

00:32:33.406 --> 00:32:34.530
and it's which one to land.

00:32:34.530 --> 00:32:36.290
I have no idea at the moment.

00:32:36.290 --> 00:32:40.900
And I can't wait to just pick
on one because then again you

00:32:40.900 --> 00:32:44.870
can get into that total
obsession, tunnel vision,

00:32:44.870 --> 00:32:48.370
and think about nothing but
that research, nothing but that.

00:32:48.370 --> 00:32:51.181
And that is the greatest state.

00:32:51.181 --> 00:32:52.930
And I also want to
write some more lyrics.

00:32:52.930 --> 00:32:54.780
But I can't do both
things at once.

00:32:54.780 --> 00:32:57.860
I need to have just one
thing in my head at a time.

00:32:57.860 --> 00:33:01.780
So I'm at this
moment, I'm not sure

00:33:01.780 --> 00:33:04.160
if it's lyrics
next or novel next.

00:33:04.160 --> 00:33:04.680
We'll see.

00:33:04.680 --> 00:33:06.180
ANANT SHUKLA: And
outside of writing

00:33:06.180 --> 00:33:07.930
I know photography
is a big passion.

00:33:07.930 --> 00:33:09.620
What else kind of drives you?

00:33:09.620 --> 00:33:11.578
POLLY SAMSON: Well
photography is a big passion

00:33:11.578 --> 00:33:13.480
because I'm not a
natural photographer.

00:33:13.480 --> 00:33:15.490
I'd say that because
I've always written

00:33:15.490 --> 00:33:19.630
and it is the thing--
for most of my life

00:33:19.630 --> 00:33:22.160
it has defined me, writing.

00:33:22.160 --> 00:33:24.940
And photography doesn't
come naturally to me.

00:33:24.940 --> 00:33:27.510
So I love something that
I have to really work at.

00:33:27.510 --> 00:33:28.930
And I love learning.

00:33:28.930 --> 00:33:31.000
And the piano is the same thing.

00:33:31.000 --> 00:33:33.590
I like things that
are incremental.

00:33:33.590 --> 00:33:36.740
So you know I've had all sorts
of things that I can juggle.

00:33:36.740 --> 00:33:39.500
And that again is a kind of
incremental learning thing.

00:33:39.500 --> 00:33:44.180
And yeah, I still play the
piano and I play guitar.

00:33:44.180 --> 00:33:46.990
So, yeah, but my
passion is writing.

00:33:46.990 --> 00:33:48.680
ANANT SHUKLA: Great, great.

00:33:48.680 --> 00:33:51.290
Are there any other
audience questions?

00:33:51.290 --> 00:33:53.470
So we're going to
start off with Polly

00:33:53.470 --> 00:33:58.326
reading a little bit, one short
passage from "The Kindness".

00:33:58.326 --> 00:34:00.700
POLLY SAMSON: So I'm going to
simply read the first three

00:34:00.700 --> 00:34:04.190
pages just set in
August 1989 this bit

00:34:04.190 --> 00:34:08.580
although the novel
spans 23 years.

00:34:08.580 --> 00:34:11.590
"Lucifer flew well for
her in the fading light,

00:34:11.590 --> 00:34:14.620
falling through the sky when
she summoned him and away again

00:34:14.620 --> 00:34:17.610
towards a great bruising sunset.

00:34:17.610 --> 00:34:19.550
She was alone on
the ridge at first,

00:34:19.550 --> 00:34:23.090
just her, the bird,
and the wide open view.

00:34:23.090 --> 00:34:26.530
It was one of those nervy summer
days of sudden strong winds

00:34:26.530 --> 00:34:28.889
that fretted the hawks
feathers as he stared at her

00:34:28.889 --> 00:34:31.900
from his perch on her gauntlet.

00:34:31.900 --> 00:34:34.850
She was wearing a long red
shirt over jeans and sandals.

00:34:34.850 --> 00:34:37.790
Her hair was breaking
free of its band.

00:34:37.790 --> 00:34:40.190
A leather pouch hung from
her belt and a whistle

00:34:40.190 --> 00:34:42.580
from a cord around her neck.

00:34:42.580 --> 00:34:45.949
The hawk braced his feet on her
wrist, making a leather tassel

00:34:45.949 --> 00:34:47.721
swing from the gauntlet.

00:34:47.721 --> 00:34:49.679
She felt the breath of
his feathers on her face

00:34:49.679 --> 00:34:50.800
as he departed.

00:34:50.800 --> 00:34:53.900
And she watched him go with
the wind right under his wings,

00:34:53.900 --> 00:34:58.450
scattering crows like drops
shaken from an umbrella.

00:34:58.450 --> 00:35:01.530
Julia was trying her best to
get it right for the bird.

00:35:01.530 --> 00:35:04.115
The morsels were small
to keep him active.

00:35:04.115 --> 00:35:09.050
A shaming 26 ounces he'd weighed
on the scales that morning.

00:35:09.050 --> 00:35:11.480
She called him with a
whistle, two short bursts.

00:35:11.480 --> 00:35:12.670
And there he was.

00:35:12.670 --> 00:35:15.490
A dark cupid's bow
firing straight at her

00:35:15.490 --> 00:35:17.420
from the heavens.

00:35:17.420 --> 00:35:19.350
She continued along
the ridge, Lucifer

00:35:19.350 --> 00:35:22.730
steady on her arm, his manic
eyes never leaving her face

00:35:22.730 --> 00:35:24.710
until she gave the signal.

00:35:24.710 --> 00:35:27.700
She sent him reeling to
and fro and neither of them

00:35:27.700 --> 00:35:32.120
knew that this was to
be their last dance.

00:35:32.120 --> 00:35:34.360
The evening started to chill.

00:35:34.360 --> 00:35:36.400
She'd almost forgotten
that Julian was supposed

00:35:36.400 --> 00:35:37.550
to be meeting her there.

00:35:37.550 --> 00:35:40.460
Or perhaps she'd
just given up hope.

00:35:40.460 --> 00:35:42.400
He was panting when
he arrived, still

00:35:42.400 --> 00:35:44.820
red in the face from the
run up the hill, his bike

00:35:44.820 --> 00:35:47.040
and its useless tire abandoned.

00:35:47.040 --> 00:35:48.670
He had the air of
a boy who'd crossed

00:35:48.670 --> 00:35:51.070
three continents to
see her, his sweatshirt

00:35:51.070 --> 00:35:52.920
knotted around his waist.

00:35:52.920 --> 00:35:54.960
Impossibly young
with hair falling

00:35:54.960 --> 00:35:58.420
over his eyes and an uncertain
lope, one leg of his jeans

00:35:58.420 --> 00:36:00.650
still tucked into his sock.

00:36:00.650 --> 00:36:02.350
He didn't dare
kiss her, he said,

00:36:02.350 --> 00:36:04.320
with the hawk glaring
at him like that

00:36:04.320 --> 00:36:06.900
from the end of her wrist.

00:36:06.900 --> 00:36:10.020
The hawk shrugged his shoulders
and she sent him flying.

00:36:10.020 --> 00:36:13.080
They kissed and when Julian
stopped to glance nervously

00:36:13.080 --> 00:36:15.480
at the sky, she took
off her gauntlet

00:36:15.480 --> 00:36:17.880
and pushed his hand inside.

00:36:17.880 --> 00:36:19.760
She urged the hawk
with her whistle,

00:36:19.760 --> 00:36:24.150
moving Julian's arm up and down,
the gauntlets tassel dancing.

00:36:24.150 --> 00:36:26.900
But Lucifer only
soared higher, the wind

00:36:26.900 --> 00:36:31.830
whispering murder into his ear
and deafening him to her call.

00:36:31.830 --> 00:36:35.400
Julia ran cursing, Julian
lolloping beside her.

00:36:35.400 --> 00:36:36.650
She grabbed back the gauntlet.

00:36:36.650 --> 00:36:38.660
And as the hawk
fell to his kill,

00:36:38.660 --> 00:36:41.070
Julian's hands were
warm on her waist

00:36:41.070 --> 00:36:43.760
and it seemed to them both
that the scream of the rabbit

00:36:43.760 --> 00:36:46.420
went on forever.

00:36:46.420 --> 00:36:49.440
It was almost midnight when
she got back to Witchwood.

00:36:49.440 --> 00:36:51.060
She'd have stayed
at Julian's digs

00:36:51.060 --> 00:36:54.580
until morning if it hadn't
been for Lucifer, bloody bird.

00:36:54.580 --> 00:36:57.670
She parked the car in the
lane, coaxed him from is crate,

00:36:57.670 --> 00:36:59.360
and clipped him on.

00:36:59.360 --> 00:37:01.790
Lucifer shook out his
feathers a little irked

00:37:01.790 --> 00:37:05.080
that somebody had
carelessly creased his cape.

00:37:05.080 --> 00:37:07.070
Fallen twigs cracked
under foot as she

00:37:07.070 --> 00:37:09.880
cut through the copse, the
bird a resentful weight

00:37:09.880 --> 00:37:12.820
on her arm, the accusatory
glitter of his eyes

00:37:12.820 --> 00:37:15.630
the only brightness
beneath the trees.

00:37:15.630 --> 00:37:16.690
The darkness dropped.

00:37:16.690 --> 00:37:18.270
The branches stilled.

00:37:18.270 --> 00:37:20.500
Witchwood stood
alone in the clearing

00:37:20.500 --> 00:37:22.930
as unexpected as a
Grimms' Brothers cottage

00:37:22.930 --> 00:37:26.300
with its wonky black
boards and crooked windows.

00:37:26.300 --> 00:37:27.820
At once she could
see a light was

00:37:27.820 --> 00:37:31.550
on though she was certain
she'd switched everything off.

00:37:31.550 --> 00:37:34.150
Her face owlish white, Julia
slipped through the back gate,

00:37:34.150 --> 00:37:36.260
whispering to Lucifer
as she transferred him

00:37:36.260 --> 00:37:40.250
to his post in the shed
and all alone up the path.

00:37:40.250 --> 00:37:44.070
Heart beating, a skittering
stone loose at the steps,

00:37:44.070 --> 00:37:47.190
she pushed the door
open with her foot

00:37:47.190 --> 00:37:49.420
and straight into the kitchen.

00:37:49.420 --> 00:37:51.960
A gasp, mostly relief.

00:37:51.960 --> 00:37:55.890
Chris, her husband,
streaky hair flat his head,

00:37:55.890 --> 00:37:59.280
his giant gray trainers kicked
halfway across the floor,

00:37:59.280 --> 00:38:01.810
chinkering his spoon in a cup.

00:38:01.810 --> 00:38:04.110
She took half a pace back.

00:38:04.110 --> 00:38:06.260
'Why the look of
surprise', he said.

00:38:06.260 --> 00:38:08.640
'I live here too, you know'

00:38:08.640 --> 00:38:12.350
Maggie, his lurcher, quivered
in disgust beside him,

00:38:12.350 --> 00:38:14.920
her nose pressed to his knee.

00:38:14.920 --> 00:38:18.770
'So here I am, home.' He
made a mockery of the word,

00:38:18.770 --> 00:38:22.810
bristling with it, pointing
his spoon at her like a weapon.

00:38:22.810 --> 00:38:25.770
'I wasn't expecting you.'
She hung the leather gauntlet

00:38:25.770 --> 00:38:29.070
on its hook, brain racing
for an alibi and stalling.

00:38:29.070 --> 00:38:30.070
'You gave me a fright.

00:38:30.070 --> 00:38:32.190
You could have been anybody.'

00:38:32.190 --> 00:38:35.000
He cursed her for the
welcome, baring teeth older

00:38:35.000 --> 00:38:38.222
than his mouth,
Nescafe and tobacco.

00:38:38.222 --> 00:38:38.930
'What did you do?

00:38:38.930 --> 00:38:40.554
Did you leave Lucifer
in the boot while

00:38:40.554 --> 00:38:43.740
'you--' 'I couldn't get the
car to start.' He snatched

00:38:43.740 --> 00:38:46.450
the leather pouch from her and
threw the leftover bits of meat

00:38:46.450 --> 00:38:49.140
to his dog, then
pulled it inside out.

00:38:49.140 --> 00:38:52.490
'If you don't clean it out,
they'll be maggots again.'

00:38:52.490 --> 00:38:55.670
He was supposed to be away
until Christmas by which time

00:38:55.670 --> 00:38:58.700
Julia promised
herself to be gone.

00:38:58.700 --> 00:39:02.120
His overalls fell open to
a Ramones t-shirt so faded

00:39:02.120 --> 00:39:04.280
you'd have to already
know the name of the band

00:39:04.280 --> 00:39:07.490
and down to a belt with
a large metal buckle.

00:39:07.490 --> 00:39:10.950
He unloaded his pockets
over the kitchen counter

00:39:10.950 --> 00:39:15.120
tobacco, Murray mints,
rolling papers, dope tin,

00:39:15.120 --> 00:39:16.710
change clattering.

00:39:16.710 --> 00:39:18.970
His hair was dotted
with gray paint

00:39:18.970 --> 00:39:21.720
like flies have been
laying eggs in it.

00:39:21.720 --> 00:39:24.310
'It's great you're so
pleased to see me', he said,

00:39:24.310 --> 00:39:28.190
'a real treat.' 'Likewise'.

00:39:28.190 --> 00:39:29.070
I'll leave it there.

00:39:29.070 --> 00:39:32.801
[APPLAUSE]

00:39:32.801 --> 00:39:33.800
ANANT SHUKLA: All right.

00:39:33.800 --> 00:39:36.540
I think we'll segue then
to the second reading

00:39:36.540 --> 00:39:38.670
from "Perfect Lives".

00:39:38.670 --> 00:39:42.080
Everybody join me in giving
a great round of applause

00:39:42.080 --> 00:39:43.876
for Ms. Polly Samson.

00:39:43.876 --> 00:39:44.376
[APPLAUSE]

00:39:44.376 --> 00:39:46.860
POLLY SAMSON: Thank you.

00:39:46.860 --> 00:39:49.640
So the thing to
say about this is

00:39:49.640 --> 00:39:54.220
I've sort of taken a few
little bits of one story

00:39:54.220 --> 00:39:58.430
and talking about real
life influencing something

00:39:58.430 --> 00:40:02.200
you might write, when I wrote
this story or just before I

00:40:02.200 --> 00:40:04.680
wrote it, I had
three friends, three

00:40:04.680 --> 00:40:07.660
wonderful, wonderful women who
were married to really, really

00:40:07.660 --> 00:40:09.040
boring men.

00:40:09.040 --> 00:40:11.980
And these really boring men
left these wonderful women

00:40:11.980 --> 00:40:14.230
for other women.

00:40:14.230 --> 00:40:18.350
And these women who seemed to
have tired of these boring men,

00:40:18.350 --> 00:40:22.671
all became stalkers
of their ex-husbands.

00:40:22.671 --> 00:40:24.170
And they would all
tell me about it.

00:40:24.170 --> 00:40:28.110
And the material was
just too good to waste.

00:40:28.110 --> 00:40:33.040
And you know the internet makes
stalkers of all of us, so yeah.

00:40:33.040 --> 00:40:34.248
Anyway it's called "Morgana".

00:40:40.090 --> 00:40:43.010
"Morgana burst into my
life, jingling and jangling

00:40:43.010 --> 00:40:45.620
armfuls of bracelets and
puffing thin cigarettes

00:40:45.620 --> 00:40:47.230
that she rolled herself.

00:40:47.230 --> 00:40:50.990
Silk flowers scattered here and
there in twists of dark hair,

00:40:50.990 --> 00:40:55.552
fresh from her crisis and
still prone to sudden tears.

00:40:55.552 --> 00:40:57.760
My shoulders were not the
kind that usually got cried

00:40:57.760 --> 00:41:01.140
on, a bit on the tense side I
suppose what with Simon working

00:41:01.140 --> 00:41:04.470
all the time and Angus and
Ivan like leaky pockets,

00:41:04.470 --> 00:41:07.840
never full no matter how
much I poured into them.

00:41:07.840 --> 00:41:10.480
Morgana's fandango,
what a nightmare.

00:41:10.480 --> 00:41:12.760
Things being thrown,
hot cups of tea

00:41:12.760 --> 00:41:16.040
across the kitchen, Mike's
clothes into marine parade,

00:41:16.040 --> 00:41:17.920
the photographs of their
wedding day removed

00:41:17.920 --> 00:41:20.760
from the top of the piano,
put back again twice,

00:41:20.760 --> 00:41:22.750
and removed again
with such force

00:41:22.750 --> 00:41:25.370
that the glass
shattered in the frames.

00:41:25.370 --> 00:41:27.110
She was wild when he left.

00:41:27.110 --> 00:41:30.450
A river of tears washing over
a fortnight's dismal blowjobs

00:41:30.450 --> 00:41:32.630
that failed to make him stay.

00:41:32.630 --> 00:41:34.970
She put half a brick through
the window of the basement

00:41:34.970 --> 00:41:37.910
he was renting one night when
he wouldn't open the door.

00:41:37.910 --> 00:41:39.930
His girlfriend Elizabeth,
who he pretended

00:41:39.930 --> 00:41:41.670
didn't live there
with him at all,

00:41:41.670 --> 00:41:44.550
looked up from playing her
oboe straight at Morgana

00:41:44.550 --> 00:41:47.720
outside on the pavement, and
laying the oboe carefully

00:41:47.720 --> 00:41:51.250
down raised her arms to
release a long skein of hair

00:41:51.250 --> 00:41:53.340
from its band,
sending it falling

00:41:53.340 --> 00:41:56.400
and swinging down her
back like molten metal

00:41:56.400 --> 00:42:00.260
and sashayed to the
telephone to call the police.

00:42:00.260 --> 00:42:01.890
Morgana's driving
is not improved

00:42:01.890 --> 00:42:04.560
when she tells me
about these things.

00:42:04.560 --> 00:42:06.600
I had, though not
without misgiving,

00:42:06.600 --> 00:42:08.860
agreed to put my life
in Morgana's hands

00:42:08.860 --> 00:42:11.200
a couple of afternoons a week.

00:42:11.200 --> 00:42:13.890
She was quite bold
when she suggested it.

00:42:13.890 --> 00:42:16.560
Mike did all the driving,
she told me one afternoon

00:42:16.560 --> 00:42:18.940
when I'd come with my
films to the studio she ran

00:42:18.940 --> 00:42:20.710
from the basement of her house.

00:42:20.710 --> 00:42:23.420
'After 29 years in
the passenger seat,

00:42:23.420 --> 00:42:25.645
I'll be needing to brush up.

00:42:25.645 --> 00:42:28.400
I never even got to touch
the radio in our car.

00:42:28.400 --> 00:42:31.410
And the steering wheel was most
definitely out of bounds', she

00:42:31.410 --> 00:42:35.230
said, the first time she sat
clutching my car's wheel.

00:42:35.230 --> 00:42:36.840
'I'm sure I could drive.

00:42:36.840 --> 00:42:39.540
I've definitely got a license
and I can remember taking a red

00:42:39.540 --> 00:42:43.310
Mini Moke right up the
middle of Portabella Market.'

00:42:43.310 --> 00:42:44.980
I was in awe of her then.

00:42:44.980 --> 00:42:46.960
I was nervous when
she developed my films

00:42:46.960 --> 00:42:48.950
and printed my
pictures, worrying

00:42:48.950 --> 00:42:52.770
that my composition was not good
or the exposures ill judged.

00:42:52.770 --> 00:42:55.260
She made prints from
the best of them.

00:42:55.260 --> 00:42:56.410
There was glamor to her.

00:42:56.410 --> 00:42:57.910
She was festooned
with it, all those

00:42:57.910 --> 00:43:01.630
bracelets she wore, the layers
of fine fabrics, the charms

00:43:01.630 --> 00:43:04.310
and old meaningful rings that
hung from her neck clustered

00:43:04.310 --> 00:43:06.400
together on a long gold chain.

00:43:06.400 --> 00:43:09.040
The hints of a rackety
life once lived up and down

00:43:09.040 --> 00:43:10.870
the Kings Road.

00:43:10.870 --> 00:43:12.830
I called for her on
Tuesdays and Thursdays

00:43:12.830 --> 00:43:15.580
at 2:30 in the afternoon
so we had a clear hour

00:43:15.580 --> 00:43:17.670
to mow down pedestrians
before I had

00:43:17.670 --> 00:43:22.320
to collect my pair of leaky
buckets from their school.

00:43:22.320 --> 00:43:26.240
Sometimes I could feel
my poor Peugeot quake.

00:43:26.240 --> 00:43:29.120
A variety of stimuli
could set Morgana off.

00:43:29.120 --> 00:43:32.150
An alabaster statuette
spied through his window

00:43:32.150 --> 00:43:34.860
flaunting its nakedness
atop his new desk.

00:43:34.860 --> 00:43:39.040
'Do you suppose it reminds him
of her?' CDs or books spotted

00:43:39.040 --> 00:43:41.020
lying on the
backseat of his car,

00:43:41.020 --> 00:43:43.510
a thick one with an
irritating title.

00:43:43.510 --> 00:43:46.010
'The man on the cover looked
to be in fear of his life,' she

00:43:46.010 --> 00:43:48.930
said, rattling my keys at
the ignition irritably.

00:43:48.930 --> 00:43:52.300
'What's he doing reading
self-help books?'

00:43:52.300 --> 00:43:55.720
Sometimes, Morgana told me,
she couldn't sleep at night

00:43:55.720 --> 00:43:58.420
and in the darkness she
tiptoed quite undetected

00:43:58.420 --> 00:44:02.110
through the perfumed gardens
of Elizabeth's Facebook.

00:44:02.110 --> 00:44:04.470
Elizabeth seemed to have
accepted Morgana's alter ego

00:44:04.470 --> 00:44:05.400
as a friend.

00:44:05.400 --> 00:44:06.950
I said it just proved
how few friends

00:44:06.950 --> 00:44:09.070
she had in the real world.

00:44:09.070 --> 00:44:12.150
Bang outside Mike's flat and
into a space either directly

00:44:12.150 --> 00:44:14.450
behind or directly
in front of his car

00:44:14.450 --> 00:44:17.150
always seemed to Morgana
to be the perfect place

00:44:17.150 --> 00:44:19.980
to practice parking
because curtains

00:44:19.980 --> 00:44:21.360
were drawn at the front.

00:44:21.360 --> 00:44:23.000
They had been since
the last time he'd

00:44:23.000 --> 00:44:24.360
allowed her over the threshold.

00:44:24.360 --> 00:44:26.400
And much to
Elizabeth's displeasure

00:44:26.400 --> 00:44:28.790
and Morgana's later
mortification,

00:44:28.790 --> 00:44:30.590
she and Mike had
ended up wrestling

00:44:30.590 --> 00:44:33.320
on the floor like bad children.

00:44:33.320 --> 00:44:36.450
Once parked, Morgana was
able to nip out and search

00:44:36.450 --> 00:44:38.400
for those little sharp
nuggets of information

00:44:38.400 --> 00:44:40.880
that she so craved,
peering through the windows

00:44:40.880 --> 00:44:42.132
of his black Audi.

00:44:42.132 --> 00:44:44.440
I watched her with her
hands against the glass

00:44:44.440 --> 00:44:46.600
of the car that had
once been her chariot

00:44:46.600 --> 00:44:49.490
and cringed as I imagined
Elizabeth or Mike seeing

00:44:49.490 --> 00:44:51.020
her there.

00:44:51.020 --> 00:44:53.440
'Awaken the Giant Within'.

00:44:53.440 --> 00:44:54.950
'What's that supposed to mean?

00:44:54.950 --> 00:44:57.950
When did he ever read books like
that?' She huffed as we pulled

00:44:57.950 --> 00:45:00.590
away in a series
of ostrich jerks.

00:45:00.590 --> 00:45:02.770
'Mirrors, mirrors' I yelled.

00:45:02.770 --> 00:45:04.950
'Silly little girl must be
telling him what to read.

00:45:04.950 --> 00:45:08.030
Self help.' Her bracelets
jangled as she thumped

00:45:08.030 --> 00:45:09.730
the steering wheel for emphasis.

00:45:09.730 --> 00:45:12.670
'He never had any trouble
helping himself', ignoring

00:45:12.670 --> 00:45:14.531
the hooting from the car behind.

00:45:14.531 --> 00:45:16.530
'What do you suppose I
did to his giant, anyway,

00:45:16.530 --> 00:45:19.530
to put it to sleep.' She
scraped the gears as she changed

00:45:19.530 --> 00:45:20.520
into third.

00:45:20.520 --> 00:45:23.260
'Sorry,' she said to me and to
the man who'd overtaken shaking

00:45:23.260 --> 00:45:24.010
his head.

00:45:24.010 --> 00:45:26.010
'And he's listening
to Ting Tings.

00:45:26.010 --> 00:45:29.680
What's he doing listening to
the Ting Tings?' Thank you.

00:45:33.580 --> 00:45:35.430
ANANT SHUKLA: Thanks
again, everybody.

